	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Small-scale fishers in west Africa voice their concerns over FPAs</h1>

			
			<h4>
												30 November 2005
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p> Representatives of three national professional small-scale fisheries organisations, CONIPAS (Senegal), FNP-artisanal section (Mauritania) and UNPAG (Guinea), on December 9th 2005, adopted a common position relating to the establishment of FPAs with the EU. They recommended that FPAs should, <i> inter alia</i>, address the following issues: </p>
<ul>

<li>
 <b>Access to resources:</b> surplus stocks that are not fully exploited, as is the case with some species in Mauritania (hake and pelagic), can be reserved for EU boats. However, an FPA with the EU must not allow for access to over-exploited stocks, in any way whatsoever, including through the transfer of vessels or the establishment of joint enterprises;<br /> </li>

<li>
 <b>Fishing zones, biological rest periods, etc: </b>experience has shown that once these elements are written into the terms of an agreement, there is little room for flexibility. When management measures such as additional biological rest periods have to be taken urgently to safeguard the resource, it is difficult to have them respected by European boats. Where fisheries management plans exist, there is no need to mention fishing zones, biological rest periods and mesh sizes in the agreement. It should suffice to state that technical measures are in compliance with national regulations of the third country, so that a breach of national ACP fisheries regulations amounts to a breach of the agreement;<br /> </li>

<li>
 <b>Financial compensation:</b> currently there is a complete lack of transparency, where neither the professionals nor the public have any idea of how the financial compensation is used. For future FPAs, conditions for total transparency need to be put in place, both in terms of agreeing on the levels of financial compensation to be paid, and on the plans for how these monies are to be spent;<br /> </li>

<li> <b>Joint enterprises:</b> FPAs must favour the formation of joint enterprises for processing and value-adding activities, and should also involve small scale EU operators. Joint enterprises that could result in overfishing and destruction of stocks and the marine environment (e.g. through vessel transfers) should be excluded.</li>

</ul>

		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p> Common position concerning negotiations of the FPAs between the EU and Senegal, Mauritania and Guinea, December 9th 2005</p><p>

<a href="http://www.cape-cffa.org/issues/UNPAG_CONIPAS_FNP_Fisheries_Agreement_(EN)_(December_2005).doc" target="_self">http://www.cape-cffa.org/issues/UNPAG_CONIPAS_FNP_Fisheries_Agreement_%2...</a> <br /> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> It is a positive development that actors from the ACP fisheries sector are getting together and voicing similar concerns. The history of EU-ACP fisheries agreements has been plagued by a lack of transparency and the exclusion of non-state actors from actively participating in negotiations. There is now a genuine opportunity to address this aspect within the new framework of FPAs, and to build flexibility into the agreements that allows for adjustments to be made, in line with fluctuations in the availability of surplus stocks.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
	</article>

